				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Although true, I think what Garrich was trying to say is although your statement is correct bari, if you were to remain ungrouped and heal your/DS/regen your bst for 1/2 the time you spent grouped and went off and grouped or solo'ed w/ your druid for the other 1/2, you would most likely earned more than 1/2 the exp on each toon than you would have if you grouped for same durration.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
What Garrish is saying - if I understand him correctly - is that the 60ish druid and the 40ish bst would get more xp combined if they group with eachother than the bst would get alone if the druid is kept outside of group. 
<br />

<br />
What I am saying is that in my opinion this is NOT true about a druid and a bst if the druid is 50% higher level. Too much xp gets wasted and the druid hardly get any xp at all.
<br />

<br />
Lets say I tried to play for 10 hours two days in a row.
<br />

<br />
On day one I kept the bst and the druid grouped. On day two I played a bst and a druid of the same levels and kept the druid outside group. My claim would then be that I could get the bst the same number of levels as he got the day before in half the time, and that my druid would get much much more xp (like 5-10 times mroe) by spending the remaining 5 hours in an appropriate high level zone. 
<br />

<br />
Bari</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
